ensington neighborhood. Operating without a license and unregulated by any government office, the recovery house provides food, shelter, company, and a bracing self-help philosophy to addicts in an area saturated with drugs and devastated by poverty. From this starkly vivid close-up, Fairbanks widens his lens to reveal the intricate relationships the recovery houses have forged with public welfare, the formal drug treatment sector, criminal justice institutions, and the local government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAlcoholicsxRehabilitationzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aInformal sector (Economics)xPolitical aspectszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aRecovery movementxPolitical aspectszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aSelf-help housingxPolitical aspectszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aSelf-help housingzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aSocial settlementszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aSubstance abuse treatment facilitiesxGovernment policyzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aWelfare recipientsxHousingzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  awelfare, philadelphia, pennsylvania, recovery, citizenship, citizen, vacant, row house, city, industry, industrial, urban, decline, phenomenon, entrepreneur, alcoholic, addict, drugs, facilities, reform, change, access, neighborhood, government, regulation, local, criminal, labor, relapse, challenges, policy, movement, activist, activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226234113423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226234113/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles